<subSubSection id="C312651DC628FFE30D83DAE0FE61FB5C" pageId="96" pageNumber="97" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BB73696C628FFE30D83DAE0FE61FB5C" blockId="96.[151,1440,151,1262]" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">
<emphasis id="B97CEA84C628FFE30D83DAE0FECFFBA4" bold="true" box="[199,335,1021,1046]" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">Comments.</emphasis>
The species name refers to this species’ occurrence in the Sierra de 
<collectingRegion id="49CCF874C628FFE30901DAE3FB27FBA7" box="[1093,1191,1022,1045]" country="Dominican Republic" name="Baoruco" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">Baoruco</collectingRegion>
. It may be endemic to this mountain range; it is not known from the other mountain ranges in 
<collectingCountry id="F31F7606C628FFE30940DD3CFB30FB88" box="[1028,1200,1057,1082]" name="Dominican Republic" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">the Dominican</collectingCountry>
Republic, where 
<taxonomicName id="4C084D15C628FFE308C3DD3FFE8AFBEF" authorityName="KITS &amp; MARSHALL" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Poecilantrops" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="96" pageNumber="97" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dominicus">
<emphasis id="B97CEA84C628FFE308C3DD3FFE8AFBEF" italics="true" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">P. dominicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been collected. The arid Valle de Nieba separating the ranges is a significant ecological barrier; flooding of the valley has repeatedly separated the Sierra de 
<collectingRegion id="49CCF874C628FFE30E28DD77FC4BFB33" box="[876,971,1130,1153]" country="Dominican Republic" name="Baoruco" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">Baoruco</collectingRegion>
as a separate island, as recently as the Pleistocene interglacials (
<bibRefCitation id="EF994B67C628FFE30C83DD90FD6FFB14" author="McLaughlin, P. P. &amp; van den Bold, W. A. &amp; Mann, P." box="[455,751,1165,1190]" pageId="96" pageNumber="97" pagination="337 - 366" refId="ref98648" refString="McLaughlin, P. P., van den Bold, W. A. &amp; Mann, P. (1991) Geology of the Azua and Enriquillo basins, Domincan Republic; 1, Neogene lithofacies, biostratigraphy, biofacies, and paleogeography. In: P. Mann et al. (Eds), Geologic and Tectonic Development of the North American-Carribean Plate Boundary. Geological Society of America Special Papers 262, pp. 337 - 366. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1130 / spe 262 - p 337" type="journal article" year="1991">
McLaughlin 
<emphasis id="B97CEA84C628FFE30F27DD93FD25FB17" box="[611,677,1165,1189]" italics="true" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">et al.</emphasis>
1991
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EF994B67C628FFE30E40DD93FC62FB14" author="Mann, P. &amp; Draper, G. &amp; Lewis, J. F." box="[772,994,1165,1190]" pageId="96" pageNumber="97" pagination="1 - 28" refId="ref98527" refString="Mann, P., Draper, G. &amp; Lewis, J. F. (1991) An overview of the geologic and tectonic development of Hispaniola. In P. Mann et al. (Eds), Geologic and Tectonic Development of the North American-Carribean Plate Boundary. Geological Society of America Special Papers 262, pp. 1 - 28." type="journal article" year="1991">
Mann 
<emphasis id="B97CEA84C628FFE30E12DD93FC17FB17" box="[854,919,1165,1189]" italics="true" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">et al.</emphasis>
1991
</bibRefCitation>
), and 
<collectingRegion id="49CCF874C628FFE3097DDD93FB18FB17" box="[1081,1176,1166,1189]" country="Dominican Republic" name="Baoruco" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">Baoruco</collectingRegion>
endemics have been documented in other animal taxa. Although not yet recorded from 
<collectingCountry id="F31F7606C628FFE30EDEDDACFC55FB78" box="[922,981,1201,1226]" name="Haiti" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">Haiti</collectingCountry>
, this species may occur there if similar habitats have been preserved.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
